## Basic Repository Operations

### git init
Initializes a new Git repository in the current directory.

### git clone <repository-url>
Creates a local copy of a remote repository.

### git status
Shows the current state of the working directory and staging area.

## Working with Changes

### git add <file-or-directory>
Stages changes for the next commit.

### git add .
Stages all changes in the current directory.

### git commit -m "commit message"
Records staged changes in the repository with a descriptive message.

### git commit --amend
Modifies the last commit (message or content).

## Branching and Merging

### git branch
Lists all local branches.

### git branch <branch-name>
Creates a new branch.

### git checkout <branch-name>
Switches to the specified branch.

### git checkout -b <branch-name>
Creates and switches to a new branch.

### git merge <branch-name>
Merges the specified branch into the current branch.

### git rebase <branch-name>
Reapplies commits from current branch on top of another branch.

### git rebase -i <commit>
Interactive rebase to edit, squash, or reorder commits.

## Remote Repository Operations

### git remote -v
Lists all remote repositories with their URLs.

### git remote add <name> <url>
Adds a new remote repository.

### git push <remote> <branch>
Uploads local commits to a remote repository.

### git pull <remote> <branch>
Downloads and merges changes from a remote repository.

### git fetch <remote>
Downloads changes from remote without merging.

### git push --set-upstream <remote> <branch>
Pushes a branch and sets it to track the remote branch.

## History and Inspection

### git log
Shows commit history.

### git log --oneline
Shows a condensed commit history.

### git log --graph --decorate
Shows commit history with branch visualization.

### git diff
Shows differences between working directory and last commit.

### git diff --staged
Shows differences between staging area and last commit.

### git diff <commit1> <commit2>
Shows differences between two commits.

### git show <commit>
Shows details of a specific commit.

## Advanced Operations

### git stash
Temporarily saves uncommitted changes.

### git stash pop
Restores the most recently stashed changes.

### git reset --soft <commit>
Resets to a commit but keeps changes staged.

### git reset --mixed <commit>
Resets to a commit and unstages changes (default).

### git reset --hard <commit>
Resets to a commit and discards all changes.

### git revert <commit>
Creates a new commit that undoes changes from a previous commit.

### git cherry-pick <commit>
Applies changes from a specific commit to current branch.

### git bisect
Binary search through commit history to find bug-introducing commit.

## DevOps and Collaboration

### git tag <tag-name>
Creates a lightweight tag pointing to current commit.

### git tag -a <tag-name> -m "message"
Creates an annotated tag with a message.

### git submodule add <url> <path>
Adds a submodule to the repository.

### git submodule update --init --recursive
Initializes and updates all submodules.

### git blame <file>
Shows who last modified each line of a file.

### git reflog
Shows a log of all reference updates.

## Configuration and Maintenance

### git config --global user.name "Your Name"
Sets the global username for commits.

### git config --global user.email "your.email@example.com"
Sets the global email for commits.

### git config --list
Shows all Git configuration settings.

### git gc
Cleans up unnecessary files and optimizes the repository.

### git fsck
Verifies the integrity of the Git repository.

### git clean -fd
Removes untracked files and directories.

## Best Practices and Tips

1. Commit Often: Make small, frequent commits with clear messages.
2. Use Branches: Develop features in separate branches.
3. Pull Regularly: Keep your local repository up-to-date.
4. Review Before Push: Use `git diff` and `git log` to review changes.
5. Use Meaningful Messages: Write descriptive commit messages.
6. Learn Rebase: Use interactive rebase for clean history.
7. Backup Remotes: Always have remote backups of your work.
8. Use .gitignore: Exclude unnecessary files from version control.

This comprehensive guide covers the most essential Git commands that developers, DevOps engineers, and software engineers encounter in their daily work.
